snippet.title: Black Lives Matter march, May 30, 2020
snippet.description:
Several hundred people participated in a march in downtown Manchester, N.H., on May 30, to protest the death of George Floyd, a black man who died while in police custody in Minneapolis on May 25, 2020.

Video and photos by NHPR's Christina Phillips.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter: Somali boxer Ramla Ali vows to give part of earnings to #BlackLivesMatter causes
snippet.description:
Ramla Ali intends to donate 25 per cent of her professional boxing earnings over her first year to charities associated to the #BlackLivesMatter movement.

The Somali boxer, signed to Anthony Joshua's management label, is making the gesture in solidarity with George Floyd, the African-American killed in police custody whose death has sparked protests in the US.

Ali's family fled war-torn Somalia as refugees after her brother had already been killed. Settling in London, she initially kept her boxing training a secret for fear her family would disapprove of the pastime for a Muslim girl.

snippet.title: Justice for George Floyd ‘Black lives matter’ ✊🏾
snippet.description:
Published on June 1,2020


Following the recent killing of George Floyd, many persons have been protesting across different state in the United States...video footage clearly shows Floyd being cuffed faced down and was kneeled on by 3 police officers one of whom was seeing kneeling in his neck... Floyd could be heard crying out “I can’t breathe” to which the officers showed no remorse...we stand with our black brothers and sister in this march for justice for Floyd and all the other black lives that was brutally taken away... “I can’t breathe”....black lives matter!!!

snippet.title: NFL Players Speak Out Against  Injustice (Black Lives Matter Tribute)
snippet.description:
Players of The National Football League produces a powerful video demanding change. The NFL commissioner Roger Godell has since apologized and admitted the NFL was wrong. Peaceful protests have been ensured despite President Trump's uproar.

Colin Kaepernick has yet to receive a proper public apology, so here is my tribute to him!

Thank you: Colin Kaepernick, Tyrann Mathieu,  Deshaun Watson, DeAndre Hopkins, Jarvis Landry,  Patrick Peterson, Patrick Mahomes, Saquon Barkley,  Ezekiel Elliot, and Odell Beckham Jr.!

R.I. P.: George Floyd, Breonna Taylor, Ahmaud Arbery, Eric Garner,  Laquan McDonald, Tamir Rice, Trayvon Martin, Walter Scott, Michael Brown Jr,  Samuel DuBose,  Frank Smart, Phillip White, Jordan Baker, and other wonderful human beings who were taken by police brutality, racism, etc.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
The StudyTube Project stands with the black community and will continue to use all of our platform for the greater good. 
We will continue to help spread awareness and do so in a way that doesn’t take the focus away from the #BlackLivesMatter movement. 

Here are a few resources you can look through to educate yourselves on the matter and be actively anti-racist:


🎥 Videos: 

Ehis’ video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Vn_iBDKm-9w&t=4s
Vee’s video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gEg_18R_0L0

Eve’s and Tolu’s Instagram Live: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hFgkXe4VYkY

📚Books:

Why I’m No Longer Talking to White People About Race - shorturl.at/vxDK0

In the words of Angela Davis, “In a racist society, it is not enough to be non-racist, we must be anti-racist.”

snippet.title: #BlackLivesMatter | They don't care about us.
snippet.description:
Hey guys, so I wanted to give a break on posting edits to say something really important. I think you all know about what's going on, and I really felt like I needed to do something to spread the message of the movement, so I did this video to show my support to #BlackLivesMatter, this video doesn't show half of the brutality that these people suffer every day but I really want to make you guys reflect about racism and everything wrong with out society. This song is very special too, and I put scenes of people I admire, like Viola Davis, movies/series that shows us that we need to fight for what is right, I really like the speech of Katniss on Mockingjay, the series "When They See us"is just incredible, and I love "The Hate U Give" too... I was not worried about HD scenes, or anything like that, I just knew I needed to do something to show my support! Hope you guys can use this video to reflect, share this with your friends and let's be on the right side :) 

Sincerely, Holy Wolf.

WAYS YOU CAN HELP! https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - police brutality | spoken word poetry
snippet.description:
The needless and brutal murder of #GeorgeFloyd is yet another reminder of our broken system of systemic racism, police brutality and the criminalisation of blackness, across society. When man helplessly says #icantbreathe and is ignored by the very people here to 'serve and protect' this is why there is the need for a Black Lives Matter movement. 
In dedication to him, and the injustice he faced, this spoken word poetry is written about the deeply harmful police brutality and senseless killing, which needs to be addressed! 
Peace and love to the family of George Floyd🖤 #BlackLivesMatter

Another life lost in America...
so maybe there could be a race problem in the united states after i’ve lost count of the deaths,
like maybe we won’t still be in denial after seeing another video of sensitive content
we can finally admit that this needs to end...until we forget. again.
until the next time another name made hashtag,
another body splashes across a friend’s insta story
a reminder that the death toll is never paused,
continually in counting,
yet lacking constant coverage,
it’s a brutal cycle running on replay, but hey, life goes on
until the next shot.

and yet it still takes a bloodbath before we can even recognise this racial hate,
why is there a required red quota for social change?
you cannot measure a struggle by the blood or the suffering or hate
that you see if so much goes unseen, so many wait
silenced by the raging roar of the united states,
but only a body bag will make it to the front page.
never the poster boy, never plaster the face of a boy both black and alive

the news headlines
are more often “black boy shot”
than “scholar”.
why are there more places for these kids in the prison system and graveyards than in college graduations?

why does it take another death for us to start paying attention?
why is breaking news always another broken family?
why do we still have to mourn those who were killed by the culture of a country who taught from crib to coffin to treat them like second class citizens?
like black bodies are only worthy of the spotlight, in the casket, once all that’s left are the rotting white bones underneath.

Sign this petition to demand justice for George Floyd- https://www.change.org/p/mayor-jacob-frey-justice-for-george-floyd?utm_source=brand_us&utm_medium=media

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter mural painted on the road to the White House in Washington DC
snippet.description:
The mayor of Washington, DC, ordered a massive “Black Lives Matter” mural painted along the road to the White House — which now has a giant fence erected around it.

Mayor Muriel Bowser contacted the DC Public Works Department for help to create the giant, yellow letters that span two blocks of 16th street in the nation’s capital.

Each of the letters span the width of the two-lane road — the paint of which began on Friday morning. 16 Street, where the mural is painted, leads to Lafayette Square and the White House.

Bowser has deemed the area with the huge Black Lives Matter lettering “Black Lives Matter Plaza” — which she designated with a street sign.

Stand up with Color Of Change and countless others.

snippet.title: Seoul 'Black Lives Matter' protesters rally for end to racial discrimination
snippet.description:
미국 조지 플로이드 시위, 한국 시민들도 동참해

Protests continue in the U.S., now more peacefully, against the death of George Floyd at the hands of police.
The protests have spread worldwide, too, including here in Seoul this weekend.
Our Choi Won-jong was there.
The protesters on Saturday, many of them wearing black shirts, held signs in both Korean and English, calling for an end to racism.
More than 100 people have gathered here in Seoul to show their solidarity with the Black Lives Matter movement, and they are marching with one message - social justice.
"To support Black Lives Matter... because we are sick and tired of all the racism that goes on against. Especially, me as a black person, we are just sick and tired of what's going on."
The protestors were chanting phrases like Black Lives Matter and I Can't Breathe.
And though police were on the scene, they were able to make their voices heard without any interference.
The protesters are far from the state of Minnesota, where George Floyd was killed, but they say their movement is global.
"I mean at the end of your day racism is not a problem that's exclusive, and isolate to United States. I think it's a problem in humanity. It's something that needs to address globally."
"I hope we can build a world in which we can breathe. Even though we live in different countries, I think the world we want to live in is the same. We will work together and create a world free of discrimination."
In Korea, more than one-hundred 20 organizations signed a joint statement last Friday paying tribute to George Floyd and criticizing police brutality.
The government, however, has not yet made an official statement on them or the worldwide movement.
Choi Won-jong, Arirang News.

#Seoul #Black_Lives_Matter #racialdiscrimination

📣 Arirang News(Twitter) : https://twitter.com/arirangtvnews

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter! By YmX
snippet.description:
Recent events have taken a toll on me and I'd normally keep quiet for the fear of being misunderstood or not saying the right words but I'm learning that I have a responsibility to use my voice in the face of injustice and nothing will be achieved through silence! 

So here I am, using my 'voice' and this is only the beginning...

We are in this together and we need to support each other and continue to use our voices or anything we have, and one day, when the glory comes...It will be ours!

snippet.title: Liverpool Black Lives Matter Protestors
snippet.description:
ID: 

A huge crowd at St George's Hall in Liverpool this evening in solidarity with the race protest movement in the US.

The wave of protests sweeping the UK is in support of the anger about violence suffered by black people at the hands of police in the US, a feeling galvanised by the death of George Floyd in Minneapolis earlier this month. 

Mr Floyd died after a police officer put his knee on the unarmed black man's neck for more than eight minutes despite him warning that he could not breathe.

snippet.title: Never Enough - The Greatest Showman | black lives matter remix
snippet.description:
This week for #musicmonday is for the culture. Too many of us are dying unjustly. We need to pray. We need to donate. We need to buy black. We need to support people in office that want to bring justice. We need to stand together. This was the only way I could think to express how I feel about recent events. No more silence. It’s time for action #blm #blacklivesmatter #greatestshowman #parody #remix

Lyrics 

I can no longer hold my breath
Can’t let it stay this way
Injustice needs to end
MLK said, “Dream with me”
But racism is louder now
Can you feel it echoing?
Raise your hand
Will you stand here with me?
Don’t wanna do this without you

Coverage of a thousand protests
And a hashtag that gets you noticed
Will never be enough
Never be enough
Four police fired is still too little
These hands are sick and tired and it’ll
Never be enough 
Never be enough

Til we’re free
Never, never
Never, never
Never, I just want
To be free
Never enough
Never enough
Never enough
Please don’t 
Kill me
I can’t breath 

Unarmed kings and queens are dying
As soon as we wake up we’re fighting
This trauma is too much
But still to hope I clutch 
Allies speak up but it’s still too little 
I raise my hands and kneel but it’ll
Never be enough
When will we be enough 

To be free
Give them pressure
Show displeasure
Let me be free, can’t you see
Is this enough 
We try to be tough
But we just want
To be free
Can’t you see
Don’t kill me
I can’t breath

snippet.title: Des manifestants de Black Lives Matter devant l'ambassade américaine à Londres | AFP Images
snippet.description:

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter: A Virtual Celebration of Black Theatre Artists
snippet.description:
Broadway Sessions will present a digital Black Lives Matter fundraising concert on June 4th. This celebration of Black Theatre Artists will feature Black performers sharing not only songs, but their thoughts  on anti racism, police brutality and how others may get involved to affect much needed change.  The concert will be live streamed on multiple platforms at 8:30pm EST. 

Artists scheduled to appear include Antoine L Smith (Ragtime, MJ the Musical), Warren Egypt Franklin (Hamilton), Ari Groover (Tina), Angela Birchett (The Color Purple, The Clark Sisters), Doulas Lyons (Beautiful, writer Polka Dots The Cool Kids Musical, Beau), Kyle Taylor Parker (Kinky Boots, Smokey Joe’s Cafe), DeMarius Copes (Dear Evan Hansen), Asmeret Ghebremichael (Legally Blonde, Dreamgirls), Brittney Mack (Six), Michael Demby Cain (Beauty and the Beast, Victor/Victoria), Laquet Sharnell (Memphis, The Lion King), Destan Owens (Rent), Joy Woods (Little Shop of Horrors),  Imari Hardon (Ave Q), singers Shavon Lloyd, Subiya Mboya and more.

Viewers are encouraged to donate to important organizations including Black Lives Matter, Black Visions Collective, Color of Change and more.

Broadway Sessions is committed to using it’s platform to promote and support Black artists and stands with the Black Lives Matter movement.

snippet.title: Australian journalists attacked live on air during Black Lives Matter protests in London
snippet.description:
Two Australian journalists have been set upon while reporting on Black Lives Matter protests in London. 

Nine News correspondent Ben Avery was crossing to the Today show this morning when he was ambushed by demonstrators and forced to abandon his live coverage. 

It comes after Nine's Europe Correspondent Sophie Walsh was attacked live on air while previewing a Black Lives Matter protest last night. 

Ms Walsh was live on the evening news in Adelaide when a man allegedly said Allahu Akbar before grabbing her. 
Her cameraman managed to chase down the attacker and hold him until police arrived.

He was allegedly found in possession of a screwdriver and arrested for threats to kill and carrying a weapon.

snippet.title: WHO'S GEORGE? BLACK LIVES MATTER(GEORGE FLOYD( من هو جورج ؟ مسألة الحياة السوداء (جورج فلويد) (مترجم
snippet.description:
BLACK LIVES MATTER

George Perry Floyd. (October 14, 1973 – May 25, 2020) was a 46-year-old African-American man who was born in Fayetteville, North Carolina, and raised in Houston, Texas. He attended Yates High School, where he played on the basketball and football teams. Floyd was a star tight end for Yates, helping them to the 1992 state championship final game. He attended South Florida Community College (now South Florida State College) from 1993 to 1995 and played on the school's basketball team. Floyd returned to Houston, where he joined the hip hop group Screwed Up Click and rapped under the stage name "Big Floyd", after entering the Houston Hip Hop cultural scene as an automotive customizer. In 2014, Floyd moved to Minnesota. He lived in St. Louis Park and worked in nearby Minneapolis as a restaurant security guard for five years, but lost his job due to Minnesota's stay-at-home order during the COVID-19 pandemic. Floyd was the father of two daughters, ages 6 and 22, who remained in Houston.

snippet.title: Giving My Knowledge and Skills to Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
In addition to speaking to your family, friends, colleagues, and industry members about the inequality in your sector of the system, consider what YOU can do with your existing privilege, your knowledge and skills. I'm "just" an artist, but I know I can teach others the power of the newest technologies.

snippet.title: BLM Protests in Denmark as Black Lives Matter Goes Global | NowThis
snippet.description:
» Subscribe to NowThis: http://go.nowth.is/News_Subscribe
» Sign up for our newsletter KnowThis to get the biggest stories of the day delivered straight to your inbox: https://go.nowth.is/KnowThis

The Black Lives Matter protests that have sprung up in the wake of the killing of George Floyd are no longer just an American movement. The George Floyd protests have spread around the world, as protests have erupted in London, Japan, New Zealand, and Denmark. 

This BLM protest in Copenhagen, Denmark is just one example of the far reaching battle against police brutality and racial injustice, as protesters chant I can't breathe in a variety of languages and cultures. Racial injustice is a truly global issue, and while the United States might have its own shameful history, the world itself can no longer deny that Black Lives Matter.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter सोशल मीडिया पर क्यों कर रहा ट्रेंड?
snippet.description:
2008 में बराक ओबामा जब राष्ट्रपति बने तो लगा कि अमेरिका में नस्लीय हिंसा की बहस अब खत्म हो जाएगी लेकिन 2020 में राष्ट्रपति डॉनल्ड ट्रंप के कार्यकाल खत्म होते-होते अमेरिका इसी बहस पर जल रहा है. ट्रम्प प्रदर्शकारियों को रोकने के लिए सेना को धमकी तो दे रहे हैं लेकिन अश्वेतो के खिलाफ हिंसा को रोकने पर वो चुप्पी साधे बैठे हैं. तमाम दुनिया में सोशल मीडिया प्लेटफॉर्म पर ट्रेंड कर रहा है #blacklivesmatter जिसका मतलब हुआ अश्वेतों की जान भी मायने रखती है..

snippet.title: Moving Protest Art: #JUSTICEFORGEORGE #BLACKLIVESMATTER
snippet.description:
George Floyd was murdered on May 25th 2020 by a Police Officer named Derek Chauvin. Chauvin knelt on Floyd's neck for 7 minutes despite Floyd begging with him saying, "please, I can't breathe" and "I'm about to die."

This tragedy has sparked protests and riots for #BlackLivesMatter not only in the US but now across the globe as people stand up against police brutality and institutionalised racism.

To those who criticise the #BlackLivesMatter movement: 
#Equality is a cause everyone should fight for. 
Whether it be through protests, fundraising, donations, petitions, music, art or film, we must do what we can to make people hear and make people see. No Justice, No Peace.

This artwork is the least I can do to continue to spread the message that we will not stand for inequality any longer, that we refuse to see human beings suffer.

"I understand that I will never be able to understand completely. But I stand with you and I will not let you do this alone. You were never meant to."

Thank you to the wonderful Dan Pacini for allowing me to use his new song, 'The Ballad of George Floyd' in this video. Dan is a good friend, a talented musician and dedicated activist and you can find more music from him and his band here: 
https://soundcloud.com/the-hypothetics 
https://instagram.com/danncheesemusic?igshid=1ed62iwww10a3

If you would like to see more of my work please subscribe to my YouTube Channel and check out my social media links:
Facebook (Art and Photography): https://www.facebook.com/RhiannonDavisVisualArt/
Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/_rhiannondavis.visualart/
Twitter: https://twitter.com/_rhiannondavis

#BlackLivesMatter #JusticeForGeorge #Activism

snippet.title: Black lives matter song; Will I Be Okay : Suburban pain
snippet.description: Black lives matter I am tired of living in a world where my very existence feels like a threat. Black lives matter and I’ll say it once and I’ll say it again and I’ll scream it from the top of my lungs until the world understands that black lives matter. This has nothing to do with black or white and everything to do with human rights. I fight for a better life because I want my children to grow up in a world where people don’t see their blackness as a threat. And the only way I can make sure 100 percent that they don’t have to feel the same pain I did growing up is by using my voice and fighting and I urge you to do the same. Whether your black white Mexican Asian middle eastern etc please stand with us please stand for human rights please let our children grow up in a world where they don’t fear getting gunned down in the street if you have compassion spread the word use your voice have those uncomfortable conversations do it for a better future where all men women and anyone else in between can live in harmony and feel safe god bless you all and please stay safe. ✊🏿✊🏼✊🏾✊🏽✊🏾

snippet.title: Coronavirus: 'Black lives matter’ BAME and ethnic minorities twice as likely to die from COVID-19
snippet.description:
Black and ethnic minorities are more than twice as likely to die from Covid than white people, an alarming new report has found.

The shocking findings shows men of working class age are twice as likely to die than women, too.

Seperate analysis has found 64 per cent of NHS and social care workers who died were from a BAME background.

Ministers ordered the review after several studies suggested that those from BAME backgrounds were more likely to catch the bug.

And it also concluded that age, and even what job you do, could affect your chances of getting it too.

The review into the risk factors of dying from coronavirus said: "The largest disparity found was by age.

"Among people already diagnosed with COVID19, people who were 80 or older were seventy times more likely to die than those under 40.

"Risk of dying among those diagnosed with COVID-19 was also higher in males than females.

While speaking about the risk to BAME communities, Matt Hancock told MPs today that "black lives matter" - the catchphrase of the massive protests throughout the US and the world, sparked by the death of a black man, George Floyd at the hands of a white policeman. 

Read more
Black and ethnic minorities twice as likely to die from Covid than white people as Hancock says ‘black lives matter’

snippet.title: dear america, black lives matter.
snippet.description:
my heart is absolutely broken. It takes a lot of courage to publish art, but the problems black people face are forever larger than my insecurities. before you decide to invalidate my opinions and pain, just know that you are not me, nor will you ever be. You are unable to relate to my, and our, pain. it is up to everyday people to love each other and to keep these tragedies from reoccurring. yes, it is true that we are one race, so let's act like it.
follow my socials:
instagram, snap and tiktok: rachelmcbriide
twitter: rachelvmcbride

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - are the stats accurate? | Professor Wilfred Reilly
snippet.description:
The US (as well as large parts of the western world) has been gripped by protests in the wake of the appalling killing of George Floyd by american police. The black lives matter movement is central to the protests, but are the claims it makes accurate? I spoke to author and academic Wilfred Reilly about this. His argument is that the majority of the black lives matter movement's central assertions are inaccurate or misleading.

I understand that this is a highly contentious and emotive topic so please feel free to leave a comment letting us know if your thoughts (but try to keep them civil if possible).

Please give the video a LIKE AND SUBSCRIBE, thanks! Also remember to LEAVE US A COMMENT letting us know what you think.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
This is a tribute to George Floyd and every person of color who has been a victim of police brutality. There has to be a change made. To say “black lives matter” is not to say that other lives does not matter. It is the simple fact that for over 400 years, black and brown people have been oppressed and discriminated against because of their skin color. Our people are disproportionately killed/abused by people of power. Our lives matter. Any “all lives matter” comments in rebuttal to “black lives matter” will be deleted. 

Spoken word by Me. All rights belong to me. 

About me:
I am a 20 year old from Arkansas, USA. I am a future music educator. ❤️

snippet.title: BREATHLESS - Original song - BLACK LIVES MATTER
snippet.description:
‘Breathless’ is an original song against police brutality and racism.

VIOLENCE is not the solution.
SILENCE is an easy solution but it not help at all. So I decided to raise my voice my way.

DISCLAIMER : 
I'm not a native English-speaker. If there's any mistake about the English, I apologize for that. Please, no hate !!! 

I am aware that I will never know how does it feel to be oppressed because of my skin color. However I've got eyes to see all this pain and this disgusting brutality against black people in the world. I want to help, I want to stand by them.

BLACK LIVES MATTER
RACISM MUST STOP 
POLICE BRUTALITY MUST STOP

#blacklivesmatter

snippet.title: John Boyega makes impassioned speech at Black Lives Matter protest in London
snippet.description:
John Boyega has issued an emotional rallying cry in support of Black Lives Matter in London's Hyde Park. Boyega's speech was widely shared on social media after video was posted by SB.TV and others

snippet.title: I can't breathe. A song for George Floyd. #BlackLivesMatter
snippet.description:
BLACK LIVES MATTER! 
It's sickening. It's hard to say something useful. It's hard to find the right words. There will never be enough words. But sometimes where words fail music speaks. I will use my voice for justice. I STAND WITH YOU! 

In the past, I sometimes closed my eyes and pretended racism wasn't a thing to protect myself and my sensitive heart. How ignorant. 
I will do better. I promise. Being a non-racist just isn't enough anymore, it probably never was. Use your voice. Educate yourself. 

#georgefloyd 

feels kind of wrong to share my Patreon right now, but in case you want to download the song: 🧡 https://www.Patreon.com/NicoleMilik 🧡

I hope this song helps you to understand, feel, reflect. Feel free to share this with your family and friends. Start the conversation at your own kitchen table.  A sad but important #MilikMonday. 

FIND ME
___________
INSTAGRAM: https://www.instagram.com/nicole.milik/

FACEBOOK: https://www.facebook.com/NicoleMilikM...

Love, 
Nicki x

snippet.title: Police Officer takes a knee outside Downing Street at Black Lives Matter march in London
snippet.description:
Subscribe to the Evening Standard on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7RQon_YwCnp_LbPtEwW65w?sub_confirmation=1

A police officer outside Downing Street was filmed taking the knee alongside protesters marching in solidarity with Black Lives Matter.

Thousands gathered in Hyde Park on Wednesday before marching on Parliament Square in response to the killing of George Floyd in the US.

Traffic was blocked in certain areas as some climbed on phone boxes and sculptures with megaphones to whip up loud chants of "silence is violence" and "say his name, George Floyd".​

Read more: https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/london-police-office-take-knee-downing-street-a4459081.html

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - Black Out Tuesday - George Floyd - Malkom X speech Forgiven FATE
snippet.description:
To follow up the NEWS
https://blacklivesmatter.com/




Black Lives Matter (BLM) is an international human rights movement, originating in the African-American community, that campaigns against violence and systemic racism towards black people. BLM regularly holds protests speaking out against police killings of black people, and broader issues such as racial profiling, police brutality, and racial inequality in the United States criminal justice system.

snippet.description:
The overwhelming majority of protesters were peaceful throughout the day but sadly minor scuffles broke out near Downing Street afternoon, with some of the crowd shouting 'f*** Boris, f*** Trump'.

Met Police confirmed two people were arrested following the disturbance.

Police forces in the UK today issued a joint statement saying they were" appalled and horrified" by the death of Floyd.

snippet.title: Dwayne Johnson’s Black Lives Matter Speech Calls for Compassionate Leader
snippet.description:
Dwayne Johnson is looking for a unifying leader. The actor took to social media and delivered a sobering message directly to the camera, showing his support for Black Lives Matter and while he never mentions Trump by name, his frustration with the sitting leadership is made clear by his criticism. "Where is our compassionate leader who’s going to step up to our country who’s down on its knees, and extend a hand and say, ‘You stand up, stand up with me because I got you, I hear you, I’m listening to you,' Johnson stated.

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER | children's books |
snippet.description:
Today, I share six children's books with you, that enforce the Black Lives Matter movement and educate children about race. These children's books spread the BLACK LIVES MATTER message and that racism should not be accepted. EVER. Children should learn from a young age to not discriminate against people because of the colour of their skin and it saddens me that racism and inequality is ever present in our society and all over the world. I hope that these books are used more and more in schools and in homes to show children that racism is of the past and should not exist in today's society. Something must be done. SOON!

I encourage parents, carers, teachers to use these books to open up discussions about race and racism with children.

Please educate yourself and others, read these books, read websites, make donations, sign petitions, speak up at protests. George Floyd didn't deserve what happened to him, no innocent man or woman deserves that, black lives matter.

Here's some useful links that you can use:
https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co/#
^^tells you all the different things you can do

donate any spare money: https://blacklivesmatter.com
or
https://www.gofundme.com/f/georgefloyd\

sign: https://www.change.org/p/mayor-jacob-...

there's so many available resources online so please do loads of research, thank you for watching.

LINKS TO THE BOOKS I SPOKE ABOUT!

My hair is beautiful by Shauntay Grant: https://amzn.to/2My9127
Sulwe by Lupita Nyong'o: https://amzn.to/2zewsui
Little leaders - Bold women in black history by Vashti Harrison: https://amzn.to/3760bSy
Dream big little one by Vashti Harrison: https://amzn.to/3cCIIT2
We march by Shane. W. Evans: https://amzn.to/375YVic
Race cars by Jenny Devenny: https://amzn.to/2Uj90mT
Something happened in our town by Ann Hazzard, Marianne Celano, and Marietta Collins: https://amzn.to/3dGez6A

Song I used (copyright free):

Intro song: Joakim Karud - By The Croft

Disclaimer: I do not own the music in this video.

snippet.title: Statue honouring slave trader Edward Colston is toppled at Black Lives Matter protest in Bristol
snippet.description:
Subscribe to the Evening Standard on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7RQon_YwCnp_LbPtEwW65w?sub_confirmation=1

A statue of Edward Colston, a 17th-century slave trader, has been toppled in Bristol by Black Lives Matter protesters.

Video footage shows the statue being pulled down using a rope.

After it falls during the protests on Sunday people can be seen dancing atop the statue and cheering.

It comes as thousands of protesters gather across the UK to march against racism following the death of George Floyd, a black man who died while in police custody in Minneapolis.

Read more: https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/black-lives-matter-protest-george-floyd-a4462046.html

snippet.title: Manifestation contre la brutalité policière / Black Lives Matter 31 mai 2020
snippet.description: Montréal, Manifestation contre la brutalité policière / Black Lives Matter 31 mai 2020. Les manifestants sont arrivés vers 17H00. Les Klaxons, les mouvements de foules et les sirènes se sont poursuivis jusqu'à 20H30 environ. J'ai vu au moins deux grands groupes de manifestants qui marchaient pacifiquement en mémoire de George Floyd. Il y a eu du grabuge dans d'autres secteurs du centre-ville. Mais vu le nombre de personnes, on peut dire que ça s'est relativement bien passé !

snippet.title: Hypocrisy 'at the heart' of the Black Lives Matter movement
snippet.description:
The Black Lives Matter movement lost a lot of support when its leaders failed to condemn the widespread violence and looting conducted in the wake of George Floyd’s death, according to Turning Point USA’s Rob Smith.

Protesters took to the street at the end of last month after George Floyd’s death in custody in the US city of Minneapolis on May 25th.

The images of Mr Floyd pinned to the floor beneath the knee of police officer Derek Chauvin inspired protests across the country.

Mr Chauvin has subsequently been charged with second-degree murder and second-degree manslaughter.

Three other offices involved in Mr Floyd’s death have also been charged.

While many protested police brutality peacefully, there were also shocking examples of violence, particularly in Minneapolis where widespread looting, riots and arson took place.

Mr Smith told Sky News the response to Mr Floyd’s death show the “hypocrisy of what is going on” in Black Lives Matter movement.

“The vast majority of people that were affected by the devastated in Minneapolis, which by the way there is devastated in New York City, devastation in Atlanta, the people who are going to be living with the effects of this are African American,” he said.

To excuse some of the brutality we saw in those riots, to excuse the destruction, to excuse the amount of people who had their livelihoods absolutely destroyed in the names of Black Lives Matter… I don’t think it’s a good thing to excuse it.”

Where a lot of the leaders of that movement truly lost me, and I believe they lost a lot of people, is when they didn’t speak out against this destruction when this first started because it helped them further their agenda.”

snippet.title: Driver ‘ploughs into George Floyd protester' at Black Lives Matter rally in Colorado
snippet.description:
A Driver was filmed speeding into George Floyd protestors in Denver on a third night of fury across America.

The driver of a vehicle ran over a protester during a George Floyd demonstration in Denver, Colorado.

Shocking video captured in Colorado appears to show a black Jeep Grand Cherokee plough into a group of protesters at a Black Lives Matter protest.

Protesters were rallying against the police-involved killing of black man George Floyd, in Minneapolis, Minnesota.

Footage from the Denver rally shows a driver speeding through a crowd of demonstrators before turning the car around and crashing into one of the protesters.

Protests, some violent, occurred across America since May 26, the day after video circulated of Minneapolis police officer Derek Chauvin pinning Floyd, 46, to the ground with his knee on his neck. Floyd died soon after, according to police.

snippet.description:
Our hearts ache today from all the horrifying thing’s that are happening. We express the need to spread awareness and remind everyone that #BLACKLIVESMATTER! All lives will matter when #BLACKLIVESMATTER 🤜🏿♥️🤛🏽 Racism is taught not born. Here’s when we have to stick together as one and let our voice be heard. We aren’t hear to spread hate but to spread love & awarness of the situation that’s been going on for decades. Be the change! Make a difference, it all starts within. To all of our protesters, thank you and stay safe out there! Many blessings a todos! Juntos podemos ser el cambio!! #GeorgeFloyd ✨🖤

snippet.title: How London united for George Floyd and Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Thousands of protesters have marched through central London in an overwhelmingly peaceful Black Lives Matter demonstration sparked after the police killing of George Floyd in America.

The demonstrators, the vast majority of whom were under 30, chanted: 'No justice, no peace, no racist police', 'I can’t breathe' and 'the UK is not innocent', in a lockdown-defying demonstration that was largely organised through word of mouth and social media away from established anti-racism groups.

snippet.description:
» Subscribe to NowThis: http://go.nowth.is/News_Subscribe
» Sign up for our newsletter KnowThis to get the biggest stories of the day delivered straight to your inbox: https://go.nowth.is/KnowThis

In US news and current events today, as the country weeps over the death of George Floyd at the hands of police brutality, celebrities and influencers are getting behind Black Lives Matter and speaking out on the senseless George Floyd death and the routine discrimination and injustice faced by Black Americans. 

In this LL Cool J video, the legendary rapper delivers a trademark LL Cool J Black Lives Matter freestyle about the state of the country, the George Floyd killing, and the righteous anger and cries for justice that have gone unheard for too long. I Can't Breathe has become a rallying cry for a genuine uprising, and this LL Cool J rap will become an anthem as the nation marches toward peace and justice.

snippet.title: Massive crowd of protesters gather at Black Lives Matter Plaza near the White House
snippet.description:
Thousands of people turned out in Washington, D.C., on Saturday for a major protest as demonstrations against police brutality and the death of George Floyd ramp up.

Officials prepared for the protests by closing a significant number of roads around the city's downtown area, with demonstrations in the nation's capital entering a second consecutive weekend.

Protesters started to congregate on 16th Street and the newly named Black Lives Matter Plaza in northwest D.C. near the White House a couple of hours before noon.


You can read more here: https://thehill.com/homenews/news/501454-huge-protest-expected-in-dc-amid-escalating-scrutiny-of-police



#GeorgeFloyd
#BlackLivesMatter
#1MillionDCSaturday

localized.description:
Thousands of people turned out in Washington, D.C., on Saturday for a major protest as demonstrations against police brutality and the death of George Floyd ramp up.

Officials prepared for the protests by closing a significant number of roads around the city's downtown area, with demonstrations in the nation's capital entering a second consecutive weekend.

Protesters started to congregate on 16th Street and the newly named Black Lives Matter Plaza in northwest D.C. near the White House a couple of hours before noon.


You can read more here: https://thehill.com/homenews/news/501454-huge-protest-expected-in-dc-amid-escalating-scrutiny-of-police



#GeorgeFloyd
#BlackLivesMatter
#1MillionDCSaturday

snippet.title: These Hands of Change - Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Do not support me. This is not to promote myself- it is to use what abilities I have to try to support something greater. 

Support the movement. Support and listen to the voices of black people. Support the peaceful protesters who are being harmed and jailed. Support the lives lost by making their losses meaningful. Support community. Support change. Support a better future. 

Educate yourself. Spread awareness. Sign petitions. Contact your local officials. Donate. Watch videos and streams whose revenue will be donated in your place. Big or small, you can help make a change. Below are only a few options. Please research and choose what you want with your own breath. 

_ Sign Amnesty International's message to Minnesota Governor Tim Walz urging a clear message against excessive force by law enforcement upon minority persons, concerning the murder of George Floyd: 
https://www.amnesty.org/en/get-involved/take-action/george-floyd-police-violence-usa/ 

_ Join ColorofChange in texting "Floyd" to 55156 urging Mayor Jacob Frey that the officers involved in the murder of George Floyd are barred from becoming police officers again and do not receive related pensions: https://www.facebook.com/colorofchange/photos/a.10150403486291067/10158122764106067/?type=3&theater 

_ Watch Zoe Amira's video series fundraiser for BLM associated protester bail funds, featuring the content of black artists: 
https://youtu.be/bCgLa25fDHM 

_ Fund non-profit independent journalism covering criminal justice: 
https://www.themarshallproject.org/donate 

_ Take care of your holistic health to protect yourself against becoming overwhelmed and prevent compassion fatigue, and forgive yourself for your limits. Every mark matters, even the little ones. Do what you can. 

And remember- Protesters are protesting, looters are looting. Do not confuse them. Do not allow the juxtaposition in media to contaminate the message.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter "...But Not Enough For Me To Post About It On Instagram" | BiancaReneeToday
snippet.description:
Today's video is very different from my normal beauty content... but due to the current state of the world I felt like it was my responsibility as a black content creator to use my platform to try to make a positive change in the world.

Today I wanted to address all of you that have yet to post anything about the racial injustice and protesting that is happening right now. I asked all of you on Instagram why you haven't said anything and got many interesting response... this video is my response to your responses.

*NOTE* I did not get to touch on every reason I was sent but please understand this video is mainly directed to the people that have nothing to lose by posting on social media. OBVIOUSLY if posting will put you in danger, will get you disowned/ kicked out of the house by your parents, or will harm your mental health in any way, please continue to do your part privately. 

If you are able to donate on this video, the money will be donated to the NAACP. Please check out their website to learn more. http://www.naacp.org Even if you can only donate $1, YOU can make a difference!

In ADDITION to this YouTube fundraiser, I will also be donating all of the money generated from monitored ads on this video to the following organizations. So if you'd like to help donate, DO NOT SKIP THE ADS ON THIS VIDEO!
Black Lives Matter Global Network
National Bail Out
Know Your Rights Camp
Black Voters Matter Fund
Black Youth Project (BYP100)
NAACP Legal Defense and Education Fund
The National Police Accountability Project
Color of Change Education Fund
Unicorn Riot
Campaign Zero
Advancement Project
The Marshall Project

I will be using this website that allows you to donate to all of the above organizations at once and will split the amounts equally. (I will update you all on how much is raised here and on Instagram @MzBiancaRenee )
https://secure.actblue.com/donate/ab_mn

For more information on Organizations and Petitions that are made to help achieve racial justice, check out these Google Docs my husband Royce created. (Thank you @RoroBeckley)

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter | Vancouver Protest 2020 | Anti Racism Rally
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter 
Hundreds gathered outside the Vancouver Art Gallery Sunday afternoon for a protest demanding justice following George Floyd’s death at the hands of Minneapolis police this week.

This is the latest Vancouver Protest 2020 which shows Anti Racism Rally. 

Protesters wore masks to prevent coronavirus spread and brought signs bearing messages such as “Black lives matter,” “silence=compliance,” and “I can’t breathe,” the latter referencing Floyd’s last words as a police officer knelt on his neck for several minutes before he died. 

There was a moment of silence held at the demonstration to honour Floyd and other victims of police brutality before speeches and calls to action. Organizers plan to have the rally stay in Robson Square and not go on a march downtown, partly to avoid coronavirus spread and partly to avoid conflict with commuters and potential anti-protesters. 

The officer who held his knee to Floyd’s neck has now been charged with third degree murder and manslaughter. But Callendar-Prasad and other demonstrators want the other officers present at the time to be charged as well.

“This is the time to fight. This is the time to unite. No matter your skin colour, your pigment, where you’re from, this is something you should care about,” they said in an Instagram video preparing for the demonstration.

#BlackLivesMatter #BLM #VancouverProtest #GeorgeFloyd #AntiRacism #protest2020 #NVAliveDiaries

snippet.title: Thousands in London protest to say 'Black Lives Matter'
snippet.description:
Thousands of people have rallied in London's Hyde Park to say that Black Lives Matter.

The crowds chanted "I can't breathe" -- a reference to the death of George Floyd, in Minneapolis, who was killed when a policeman knelt on his neck.

Sky's Home Affairs editor Jason Farrell reports from London.

snippet.title: เสียงของผู้ประท้วง Black Lives Matter ในอเมริกา
snippet.description:
ผู้ชุมนุมออกมาประท้วงในเมืองต่าง ๆ ทั่วสหรัฐอเมริกาติดต่อกันเป็นเวลาหนึ่งสัปดาห์ เพื่อประท้วงการเสียชีวิตของ จอร์จ ฟลอยด์ ชายแอฟริกันอเมริกันวัย 46 ปี ระหว่างที่เขาถูกตำรวจจับกุมตัวในเมืองมินนีแอโปลิส รัฐมินนิโซตาในวันที่ 25 พฤษภาคม

ผู้สื่อข่าววีโอเอได้พูดคุยกับผู้ชุมนุมบางส่วนที่มาประท้วงหน้าทำเนียบขาว ว่าอะไรเป็นสาเหตุให้พวกเขาเข้าร่วมการเคลื่อนไหวครั้งนี้

Originally published at - https://www.voathai.com/a/us-protesters-in-their-own-words-voices/5444866.html

snippet.title: [Claves] #BlackLivesMatter: racismo y capitalismo en Estados Unidos
snippet.description:
La enorme rebelión antirracista en Estados Unidos, a raiz del brutal asesinato de George Floyd, puso en las calles otra vez al movimiento Black Lives Matter contra la violencia policial racista en todo el país. Entrevistamos a: 
Julia Wallace, activista y editora de Left Voice, el sitio de la Red Internacional de La Izquierda Diario, en Los Ángeles, California
James Early, investigador del Instituto Smithsoniano y de la Universidad de Columbia
Madeleine Freeman, activista e integrante de Left Voice en Nueva York

snippet.title: DJ K-Time on #BLACKLIVESMATTER 2020 !
snippet.description:
The world is a messed up place. We need your support now more than ever. We are tired. We are exhausted. The colour of our skin shouldn’t determine our fate. We just want to be treated as equals. 

This stand is for awareness around justice & equality. For those brothers and sisters who have experienced similar stereotypes as us. 

This goes out to any and everyone who has been wrongfully/ unlawfully abused in any way by Police, those documented as well as those that go unseen all over the world. If you mess with this, please share this video. ✊🏿

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER!
snippet.description:
BLACK LIVES MATTER! 

There are two black deaf organizations worth looking into

1) National Black Deaf Advocates, Inc. (NBDA)

They are advocates for civil rights and access through education, employment and social services for all black deaf and hard of hearing individuals. 

https://www.nbda.org/content/donate

2)Transformative Deaf Education. 

They aim to promote transformative pedagogy in deaf schools and programs. 

https://www.transformdeafed.org/

Find ways to promote these orgs!

H/T Stacy

Video narrated by Kathleen L. Brockway

snippet.title: Peaceful Black Lives Matter Protesters Get Creative | NowThis
snippet.description:
» Subscribe to NowThis: http://go.nowth.is/News_Subscribe
» Sign up for our newsletter KnowThis to get the biggest stories of the day delivered straight to your inbox: https://go.nowth.is/KnowThis

In US news and current events today, the Black Lives Matter protests have continued to boil over in over 140 cities across the US. Most stories you see are of riots, looting, and police brutality, but the George Floyd protests have been predominantly peaceful, and these Black Lives Matter protesters have come up with creative ways to have their voices heard in a peaceful manner. 

From the Cupid Shuffle dance to taking a knee in powerful moments of silence, peaceful protesters are simply trying to make a difference in the world and fight for racial justice, equality, and against police brutality. The BLM protests have opened the eyes of the world to injustice, and as the unrest continues, we should focus on the vast majority of peaceful protestors instead of the few bad actors trying to turn a beautiful movement into a riot.

snippet.title: Black Lives and Voices Matter: an art exposition (fundraiser closed!)
snippet.description:
Hi everyone!
Once again I wanted to thank you all for the massive support on this project, and I’m so proud of all the good that you all have created just by watching. I hope you’ve found some new artists to enjoy and found a desire to always lend a helping hand where you can!

Recently, I spoke with a representative at YouTube about the video fundraiser and it was found to violate Google monetization guidelines, in that it encourages “users to click or watch ads to increase the contribution” and I am working with them to amend that so that the video can return and stay up!
However, because YouTube so believed in the essence of the project, they have committed to making a donation equal to what all of you have raised in the name of the project. I’m still looking at which organisations will get what, and the final donation amount, but to say a phrase i’ve gotten very used to saying this week, “I’ll let you know when I know!”

The video will still be up on my channel although you’ll notice there’s no more ads to watch, and the title and intro may be a little different, but I still want you all to be able to enjoy the supremely talented artists involved. Please check them out on all of their listed social media, for this project wouldn’t be possible without them!

I’d also like to thank all of the media outlets and creators using their platforms to give this project some shine. Your dedication to using your voice to share and do good work speaks volumes and I am entirely grateful. Perhaps more importantly, to all of you people who shared this video on your instagram, spoke about it with your friends and families, tweeted and watched and were excited at a way to help that you couldn’t otherwise, I am BEYOND proud of you, and thank you for being part of the power behind social change. 

Thank you so so much everyone!
As always, I’ll keep you posted!
Love, Zoe 💗

In addition to watching this video and listening to the great artists in it, here are some petitions to sign in relation to these tragic losses and other ways to help.

https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co

snippet.title: Small Black Lives Matter protest in Tel Aviv
snippet.description:
(2 Jun 2020) Hundreds of people protested outside a US diplomatic office in Tel Aviv on Tuesday to decry the killing of George Floyd.
The protesters held signs reading "Black Lives Matter" and carried placards bearng Floyd's name.
Floyd, a 46-year-old man, died in Minneapolis last week after a police officer pressed his knee into his neck for several minutes even after he stopped moving and pleading for air.
Some protesters wrote the name of Solomon Teka, an 18-year-old Ethiopian Israeli, shot last year by an off-duty officer who claims he and his family felt threatened from a group of rioting teenagers while at a playground in the city of Haifa, northern Israel.
Ethiopian Israelis complain of racism, lack of opportunity, endemic poverty and routine police harassment.
Ethiopian Jews began arriving in large numbers in the 1970s and many were airlifted to Israel in clandestine operations in the 1980s and '90s during periods of unrest. 
The community is now estimated at approximately 150,000, or around two percent of the country's population.

Find out more about AP Archive: http://www.aparchive.com/HowWeWork

snippet.title: "The Colors of Our Skin" an original song. Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
I cannot not write a song about the state of the world right now and all of the hurt, the pain and the losses of many. Though I will never ever be able to understand the experiences of others, I WILL STAND WITH YOU AND FOR YOU to demand justice for George Floyd and many others. This song is called, "The Colors of Our Skin" and I really hope you guys can connect to it in some way, shape or form. Have those conversations, sign petitions, be proactive and spread love and life. We need to stand up and stand together. #Blacklivesmatter #RipGeorgeFloyd  
BUSINESS EMAIL: livreichley@gmail.com 

Lists of organizations to donate to: 
- Fair Fight: fairfight.com
- Equal Justice Initative: eji.org
- NAACP Legal Defense Fund: naacpldf.org
- Color of Change: colorofchange.org
- Bail Project: bailproject.org
- Campaign Zero: joincampaignzero.org
- Black Lives Matter: blacklivesmatter.com
- ACLU: aclu.org

Lyrics: 
The colors of our skin don't label who we are within, I feel so sad.
 The colors of our skin are predetermined whos to win, its just so bad. 
& the state that we are living, in a world thats just so cold. 
Now poeple all are dying & a good man just was choked. 
He's crying out for his mama, but all they saw was color. 
If we are all brothers & sisters why arent we treated equally? Equally.
 We're the colors of the rainbow we must stand with one another raise our voices & our hands until we are equally. 
Treated equally.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Protest: This Is Tulsa: Part II

#BlackLivesMatter #Tulsa #Protest

Do you know what makes Tulsa such an amazing city? It's the people who live here. To have such an outspoken and diverse community of citizens who want the best for their city and ALL the people who live here, and are willing to be active and vocal about those desires through peaceful protest.

snippet.title: DISKUSI: #BLACKLIVESMATTER DAN PAPUA
snippet.description:
Senin (25/5) lalu, George Floyd (46), seorang warga Amerika berkulit hitam lehernya diinjak menggunakan dengkul oleh anggota Polisi AS berkulit putih, hingga membuatnya kehabisan nafas dan tewas. Kejadian tersebut dipicuh saat Floyd diduga melakukan tindakan pidana penipuan dan pemalsuan ketika berbelanja di sebuah toko di kota Minnepolis.

Kejadian tersebut terekam dan tersebar cepat di sosial media hingga mengundang protes besar-besaran. Kejadian ini juga menjadi topik hangat di sosial media di seluruh dunia, ditandai dengan penggunaan tagar #BlackLivesMatter. Gaungnya juga sampai ke Indonesia. Orang Indonesia turut mengecam tindakan kepolisian AS tersebut dengan turut menyuarakan tagar serupa. 

Jika ingin jujur, Indonesia juga bukannya bersih dari kasus diskriminasi rasial terhadap orang berkulit hitam. Orang Papua sebagai representasi dari orang kulit hitam kerap mendapatkan diskriminasi, terutama dilakukan oleh aparat keamanan Indonesia. 

Kejadian hampir serupa dengan yang dialami George Floyd juga pernah terjadi di Indonesia, tepatnya di Yogyakarta. Saat itu pada bulan Juli 2016, asrama mahasiswa Papua dikepung oleh aparat dan ormas selama hampir 2 hari.

Salah seorang mahasiswa bernama Obby Kogoya yang hendak masuk memberikan bantuan makanan ke dalam asrama dihadang, dituduh membawa senjata tajam dan hendak ditangkap. Obby yang berupaya melarikan diri dikejar, dan dijatuhkan ke tanah sembari diinjak. Dia kemudian dikenakan tuduhan melawan petugas. 

Masih segar dalam ingatan kita ketika Asrama Papua di Surabaya dikepung oleh aparat keamanan beserta ormas pada Agustus 2019 lalu. Pengepungan disertai dengan tindakan diskriminasi rasial dengan teriakan "Monyet" Kepada penghuni asrama. Kejadian ini memicu protes besar-besaran tidak hanya di Papua. 

Lantas bisakah kampanye #BlackLivesMatter juga disematkan pada orang Papua?

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter: If They Can't Breathe, None of Us Can
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter and we need to amplify their voices right now. We need to stand in solidarity because they are fighting for justice. They are fighting against police racism, violence and brutality that kills Black people. 

They are standing for the right to life - something we can all lose if we allow police to continue lethal racism. If Black people can't breathe, none of us can.  

Justice for George Floyd, Breonna Taylor, Ahmaud Armbery, Eric Garner, Michael Brown Jr., Duane Christian, Andrew Loku, Jermaine Carby, D'Andre Campbell and the thousands of other precious lives lost.

Here is the Black Lives Matter website:
https://www.blacklivesmatter.com/

Recommended reading: Desmond Cole's "The Skin We're In: A Year of Black Resistance and Power" published by Double Day Canada:
https://amzn.to/3eynmYb

Here is my Warrior Life Podcast interview with Desmond Cole, journalist, best-selling author and social justice warrior advocating against anti-Black racism and violence by police and society:
https://www.soundcloud.com/pampalmater/desmond-cole-on-anti-black-racism-in-canada-us

Please also check out Robyn Maynard's "Policing Black Lives: State Violence in Canada: From Slavery to the Present" published by Fernwood Publishing:
https://amzn.to/3dkKlWn

Here is my Warrior Life Podcast interview with social justice warrior Robyn Maynard, Black feminist writer, activist and educator:
https://www.soundcloud.com/pampalmater/robyn-maynard-on-anti-black-racism-in-canada

snippet.title: Bowser: Black Lives Matter Sign Sends Message that 'Black Humanity Matters'
snippet.description:
Mayor of Washington DC Muriel Bowser says people around the country want their voices "heard" and "there are people who are craving to be heard and to be seen and to have their humanity recognized."

Bowser comments came Friday in explaining to reporters why city workers and volunteers painted the words Black Lives Matter in enormous bright yellow letters on the street leading to the White House.

"We know what's going... on in our country. There's a lot of anger, there's a lot of distrust of police in the government. There are people who are craving to be heard and to be seen and to have their humanity recognized. And we had the opportunity to send that message loud and clear on a very important street in our city."

"That message is to the American people that black lives matter, black humanity matters," said Bowser.

"And we as a city raise that up as part of our values as a city."

The street-painting project follows Bower’s verbal clashes with the Trump administration over the response to protests of the killing of George Floyd in Minneapolis.

Bowser has complained about the heavy-handed federal response and called for the removal of out-of-state National Guard troops.

She says their differences highlight the need for D.C. to be a state and have more control over its internal affairs.

While not addressing the painted mural, President Trump continued his attacks on Bowser in tweets Friday.

“The incompetent Mayor of Washington, D.C., MayorBowser, who's budget is totally out of control and is constantly coming back to us for ‘handouts,' is now fighting with the National Guard, who saved her from great embarrassment over the last number of nights," he tweeted. "If she doesn't treat these men and women well, then we'll bring in a different group of men and women!”

The mayor fired back "that we all have to just refocus on on what's in front of us."

"Our nation is hurting. It's in need of healing and leadership at all levels, all the way from the top to mayors like me and to all of us to focus on how we bring people together."

The city's police chief Peter Newsham also talked about the continued protests and they "anticipate numbers that are larger than any of the numbers that we've seen to this point," on Saturday.

"The critical thing for us and ensuring that the city is safe when we have large gatherings outside of the public health issues is to ensure that we don't have people who are going to be inclined to be involved in bad behavior. So that's more of our focus than the actual numbers."

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter & Music: Documenting Contemporary Culture
snippet.description:
A panel of ethnomusicologists and contributors to the book "Black Lives Matter and Music" looked towards the present state of the movement to discuss economic injustices, gentrification and cultural displacement, as well as education disparities as enduring kinds of violence. The 2018 scholarly volume "Black Lives Matter and Music: Protest, Intervention, Reflection" collected critical studies which draw from ethnographic research and personal encounters to illustrate how scholarly research and teaching about the role of music in the Black Lives Matter movement can contribute to public awareness of social, economic, political, scientific and other injustice in our society. Michael Brown was shot and killed by police in 2014, catapulting digital activism from social media hashtags to uprisings in the streets. #SayHerName, a protest of police violence against Black women, followed. Black Lives Matter as a movement has been ardently committed to revealing who people are, but it is also rooted in a concern with revealing how things work. Systematic inequality was the reason for Alicia Garza's rallying cry for #BlackLivesMatter in 2013 after the acquittal of the killer of the unarmed 17-year old Trayvon Martin. Panelists also discussed how musicians continue to provide the soundtrack for the Black Lives Matter movement. Presented with the support of the Daniel A.P. Murray Association.  

- Fernando Orejuela is a senior lecturer in folklore and ethnomusicology and adjunct professor of African American and African diaspora studies and Latino studies at Indiana University. He is a co-editor of the book "Black Lives Matter and Music: Protest, Intervention, Reflection" with Stephanie Shonekan.

 - Folklorist and ethnomusicologist Stephanie Shonekan is a professor and the chair of the W.E.B. Du Bois Department of Afro-American Studies at University of Massachusetts, Amherst. She is a co-editor of the book "Black Lives Matter and Music: Protest, Intervention, Reflection" with Fernando Orejuela. 

- Alison Martin is a contributor to the volume "Black Lives Matter and Music: Protest, Intervention, Reflection." 

For transcript and more information, visit https://www.loc.gov/item/webcast-9189

snippet.title: CURTISS THE PIMP - BLACK LIVES MATTER (A Tribute To George Floyd) - w/ subtitles
snippet.description:
Hi !
Following the recent events, I choose to break the silence to pay a tribute to George Floyd, afro-american man killed by the police, with an Indie-Pop styled composition of my own. The murder of George Floyd is an intolerable act and not an isolated case. Those racist crimes happen as well in the US than everywhere else in the world (even here in France) and that is why we're all involved and must stood up against it.

We can all make a significant gesture by donating to the official George Floyd memorial fund, here : https://www.gofundme.com/f/georgefloyd

Follow me on Facebook : https://www.facebook.com/Curtiss-The-Pimp-111081887271202/

Follow me on Instagram : https://www.instagram.com/curtissthepimp/

#blacklivesmatter

snippet.title: Freedom; where are you? #BLACKLIVESMATTER
snippet.description:
[1080p + headphones] 

➾ Legenda em português disponível.

"𝐼𝑡 𝑖𝑠 𝑖𝑚𝑝𝑜𝑠𝑠𝑖𝑏𝑙𝑒 𝑡𝑜 𝑏𝑒 𝑢𝑛𝑎𝑟𝑚𝑒𝑑 𝑤ℎ𝑒𝑛 𝑦𝑜𝑢𝑟 𝑏𝑙𝑎𝑐𝑘𝑛𝑒𝑠𝑠 𝑖𝑠 𝑡ℎ𝑒 𝑤𝑒𝑎𝑝𝑜𝑛 𝑡ℎ𝑒𝑦 𝑓𝑒𝑎𝑟."  ✊🏽✊🏾✊🏿

Warning: this description will be very emotional, sorry for that.

A few years ago my mother decided to have a conversation with me, a conversation that I forced myself to never forget. I must have been 7 or 8 years old, and I remember I came home crying, because some boys had teased me in school. Then she told me that I shouldn't let myself be overwhelmed by certain people who had the wrong knowledge. That I should be proud of being black, proud of our origins. 
The years started to pass and I heard a lot of people saying that "this kind of thing did not exist in my country" (Brazil), that there is no racism here and I really wanted to believe that this is true. But the past few weeks have been difficult to take.
We are dying, we are being left there. NO MORE!
If you can, take a moment to make donations, or even to sign petitions.
THIS IS THE TIME FOR CHANGE, SAY NEVER AGAIN!

♦ Here you can find more informations: https://twitter.com/kiesdaya/status/1265782360252887040

JUSTICE FOR GEORGE FLOYD!
JUSTICE FOR JOÃO PEDRO!
JUSTICE FOR ALL WHO HAVE BEEN LOSING THEIR LIVES FOR YEARS ONLY FOR THE COLOR OF YOUR SKIN!
✊🏽✊🏾✊🏿

☂ INFO:

▽ Fandom: The Hate U Give
▽ Song: in the end;
▽ Coloring: Jula Misiak

☂ 

Where to find me:

A few years ago my mother decided to have a conversation with me, a conversation that I forced myself to never forget. I must have been 7 or 8 years old, and I remember I came home crying, because some boys had teased me in school. Then she told me that I shouldn't let myself be overwhelmed by certain people who had the wrong knowledge. That I should be proud of being black, proud of our origins. 
The years started to pass and I heard a lot of people saying that "this kind of thing did not exist in my country" (Brazil), that there is no racism here and I really wanted to believe that this is true. But the past few weeks have been difficult to take.
We are dying, we are being left there. NO MORE!
If you can, take a moment to make donations, or even to sign petitions.
THIS IS THE TIME FOR CHANGE, SAY NEVER AGAIN!

snippet.title: John Boyega gives passionate Black Lives Matter speech at George Floyd protest in Hyde Park
snippet.description:
Star Wars actor, John Boyega, joined thousands of protesters for a Black Lives Matter rally in London today sparked by George Floyd's death.

Helicopters flew overhead of Hyde Park as the crowd of demonstrators swelled and chants of "police the police" filled the air before the group started to march.

John Boyega made a passionate call to arms through multiple megaphones as he spoke to the crowd of around 15,000 gathered in central London.

He told the protesters: "We are a physical representation of our support for George Floyd.

"We are a physical representation of our support for Sandra Bland. We are a physical representation of our support for Trayvon Martin. We are a physical representation of our support for Stephen Lawrence.

"Every black person in here remembered when another person reminded you that you were black.

"So none of you out there, all those protesters on the other side, protesting against what we want to do, protesting against what we want to try and achieve, burn you, this is so vital."

The Star Wars actor continued: "I need you to understand how painful this s**t is. I need you to understand how painful it is to be reminded every day that your race means nothing and that isn't the case anymore, that was never the case anymore."

The activists have been asked to maintain social distancing and wear protective masks at the peaceful protest to protect against coronavirus

Read more

snippet.description:
A PRAYER FOR ALL OUR BROTHERS AND SISTERS IN THIS TIME. 

Almighty Father,

Violence, anger and hate are running the streets that you have created. Satan has stolen, killed and destroyed what you have made for us. There is no peace in the land. There is no justice amongst your people. The sinful crimes of the enemy have made the hearts of your children heavy. Hear our cries heavenly King, see our pain O Righteous One and feel our hurt. 

Scripture says that “The Lord is a shelter for the oppressed, a refuge in times of trouble. Those who know your name trust in you, for you, O Lord, do not abandon those who search for you”, (Psalms 9:9-10). Let your children be reminded that in this season of pain, we must search for your grace to fall upon your people, so that you may restore peace and justice in the land.

Matthew 5:44 “But I say, love your enemies! Pray for those who persecute you!”

Father, we pray for those who persecute us and hate us, we declare a veil of protection over us all in this season. We pray that we may find refuge and security in your scriptures. We pray for the families that have lost loved ones to the unjust. We pray for our spirits to be filled with faith and strength so that we are able to cast away all works of satan. 

May your will and you will alone be done over the land. May your blessings be on your people. 

Psalms 46:10 “Be still, and know that I am God”

AMEN.

#BLACKLIVESMATTER #BLACKOUTTUESDAY

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - Minneapolis - george floyd türkçe
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter - Minneapolis - george floyd türkçe


#BlackLivesMatter. Sign a petition. Make a donation. Get informed. Make a phone call. Do it all here: https://ellen.tv/2Azjfwb

In US news and current events today, the Black Lives Matter protests have continued to boil over in over 140 cities across the US. Most stories you see are of riots, looting, and police brutality, but the George Floyd protests have been predominantly peaceful, and these Black Lives Matter protesters have come up with creative ways to have their voices heard in a peaceful manner. 


From the Cupid Shuffle dance to taking a knee in powerful moments of silence, peaceful protesters are simply trying to make a difference in the world and fight for racial justice, equality, and against police brutality. The BLM protests have opened the eyes of the world to injustice, and as the unrest continues, we should focus on the vast majority of peaceful protestors instead of the few bad actors trying to turn a beautiful movement into a riot.

Played by Arshia Jahanpour:
YOUTUBE: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC4an...
INSTAGRAM : https://www.instagram.com/arshiajahan...

snippet.title: London Black Lives Matter protest over justice for George Floyd
snippet.description:
BLACK Lives Matter protesters fill London streets over the death of George Floyd in the US.

People gather in Parliament Square, chanting 'No Justice No Peace' in the memory of George Floyd, a black man, who died after a white police officer knelt on his neck.

The 46-year-old was handcuffed and on the ground in Minneapolis earlier this week before falling unconscious.

Video of him pinned down, which has gone viral, shows Mr Floyd begging for air saying, "please, I can't breathe" and "don't kill me".

Protests have since flared up across the US, with the movement against police brutality going global.

On Saturday afternoon protesters in London carried placards reading "solidarity" and "Black lives matter".

Some read "the UK is not innocent" as dozens of people marched through Peckham, stopping buses and cars on the main road.

Read more
Black Lives Matter protesters block streets in London and promise more UK demos over death of George Floyd in US
https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/11747570/black-lives-matter-london-protest-george-floyd/

On Saturday afternoon protesters in London carried placards reading "solidarity" and "Black lives matter".

Some read "the UK is not innocent" as dozens of people marched through Peckham, stopping buses and cars on the main road.

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER: COMO OS FAMOSOS ESTÃO CONTRIBUINDO?
snippet.description:
Se não bastasse a pandemia que estamos encarando, o mundo parou para, mais uma vez, levantar a bandeira do Black Lives Matter. O movimento, que no Brasil ficou conhecido como Vidas Pretas Importam, tomou conta das notícias nos últimos dias por causa da morte do ex-segurança George Floyd, que foi imobilizado por um policial branco com o joelho, em Minneapolis, nos Estados Unidos. Além disso, aqui no Brasil, tivemos o caso do João Pedro, adolescente de 14 anos que foi assassinado com um tiro nas costas no Complexo do Salgueiro, em São Gonçalo, no Rio de Janeiro. 

Diante dos casos recentes, o movimento Black Live Matter, que começou na época do governo Obama, em 2013, tomou proporções gigantescas e dominou as ruas e as redes sociais. Com tamanha repercussão, grandes celebridades estão usando sua influência e sua voz para poder protestar diante tamanha indignação.

Ariana Grande foi uma das artistas que foram às ruas.  A cantora saiu nas ruas de Minnesota, nos Estados Unidos, para fazer sua parte. Com um cartaz escrito Black Lives Mattter, ela caminhou junto com outros protestantes.

Quem também saiu de casa para protestar, foi a cantora Helsey. Junto com o namorado, Yungblud, ela chegou a postar alguns stories em seu Instagram, mostrando sua participação.

Sempre presente nas redes sociais, Viola Davis fez questão de publicar e divulgar uma petição que está recolhendo assinaturas, chamada Justice João Pedro e que tem como objetivo recolher 1.500.000 assinaturas e pressionar o governo do Rio de Janeiro. Além da atriz, a cantora Janelle Monáe também usou o Twitter para divulgar o abaixo assinado de João.

Katy Perry e Harry Styles decidiram ajudar de outra forma. Os cantores resolveram fazer doações para os fundos que pagam as fianças dos manifestantes que acabam sendo presos. No Twitter, Harry deixou claro que agora não basta não ser racista, é preciso ser anti racista. Além disso, anunciou em outro post que estava realizando a doação.

Beyoncé gravou um vídeo no Instagram, pedindo justiça par George Floyd, divulgando a petição que fizeram para o ex-segurança e afirmando que essa é uma luta de todos contra a brutalidade que está acontecendo.

#famosos #ofuxico #blacklivesmatter

Infused with the Word of God

Black lives matter! 
Black lives matter.

Another life; another tragedy.

Make it love. Love in totality!

To tread on serpents and scorpions,

That ye may be able to withstand in the evil day, 
And having done all, to stand.
Stand therefore, 
Having your loins girt about with truth, 
And having on the breastplate of righteousness;
And your feet shod with the preparation of the gospel of peace;
Above all, taking the shield of faith, 
Wherewith ye shall be able to quench all the fiery darts of the wicked.
And take thee the helmet of salvation, 
And the sword of the Spirit, 
Which is the word of God.

Yeah, no weapon formed against me shall prosper.

I rebuke you!

For all people!

Black lives matter!
Black lives matter.
Black lives matter!
Black lives matter.
Black lives matter!
Black lives matter.
Black lives matter!

If a man say, I love God, 
(Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter)
And hateth his brother, he is a liar: 
For he that loveth not his brother,
(Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter)
Whom he hath seen, How can he love God,
Whom he hath not seen?

Dearly beloved, 
(Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter)
Avenge not yourselves, but rather give place unto wrath: 
for it is written, Vengeance is mine; I will repay, saith the Lord.

Come, my people, 
(Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter)
enter thou into thy chambers, 
and shut thy doors about thee: 
hide thyself as it were for a little moment,
(Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter) 
Until the indignation be overpast.

Black lives matter!

Black lives matter!

Black lives matter!

Black lives matter!
 
I Can Breathe!

I Can Breathe!

Let everything that have breath praise the lord.
Hallelujah!

Love the Lord thy God with all thy heart, 
With all thy soul, With all thy mind.
Love thy neighbor as thyself.

I love you!
Black!

snippet.title: Documentary: Why Black Lives Matter
snippet.description: After the killing of George Floyd by police officer Derek Chauvin by kneeling on the persons neck I look into wider instances of black history and the black lives matter movement. I look into the history of African Americans in the USA from the start as being slaves to the civil war and the fugitive slave act. I look into other black icons like Rosa Parks and Martin Luther King Jr and how they managed to get rid of the black codes to bring about the civil rights movement. Finally I compare what has happened since to examine whether president Obama or Trump have really done enough to address the injustice that black Americans are more likely to face police brutality.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protesters rally in London over killing of George Floyd - LIVE
snippet.description:
BLACK Lives Matter protesters filled central London streets over the death of George Floyd in the US.

People gather in Parliament Square, chanting 'No Justice No Peace' in the memory of George Floyd, a black man, who died after a white police officer knelt on his neck.

The 46-year-old was handcuffed and on the ground in Minneapolis earlier this week before falling unconscious.

Video of him pinned down, which has gone viral, shows Mr Floyd begging for air saying, "please, I can't breathe" and "don't kill me".

Protests have since flared up across the US, with the movement against police brutality going global.

On Saturday afternoon protesters in London carried placards reading "solidarity" and "Black lives matter".

Some read "the UK is not innocent" as dozens of people marched through Peckham, stopping buses and cars on the main road.

Read more
Black Lives Matter protesters block streets in London and promise more UK demos over death of George Floyd in US
https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/11747570/black-lives-matter-london-protest-george-floyd/

snippet.title: Fleur East's Black Lives Matter Rap Roulette Is Incredibly Powerful | Hits Radio
snippet.description:
Hits Radio Breakfast's Fleur East's Rap Roulette was about Black Lives Matter. Her lyrics are incredibly powerful, read the lyrics below.
 
Black lives matter that’s the message that’s the fight, the fight against racism and not against white / It’s a movement with a message that is centuries old, so if you stand against injustice then speak up and be bold 

We’ve seen everybody come together, stay at home and work together fighting against a virus that we can’t even see / Now we face another virus one called racism, and silence isn't gonna save lives or protect you and me. 

8 minutes 46 seconds can you believe?! / George Floyd was held down saying he couldn’t breathe 

It’s time to stand up. Time to put your hands up. Time to understand love’s the answer and enough is enough / People fear for their lives through the shade they were painted / Can you see the picture has been tainted? 

The hashtag does not accuse you or exclude you, saying all lives matter is only seeing what you choose to, if you don’t have a clue it’s like crashing a stranger's funeral and screaming ‘yeah I lost someone too!’

The inequality, complexity, the pain and the perplexity / The gunning and running and shunning and numbing the pain, the sheer immensity 

We’re meant to be in this together so speak up for your brothers for your sisters, sons and daughters for the slaughtered 

Born to a black mother and my father was white / My future children will be black and we’ll continue the fight 

Do something, say something yeah, we all have a voice / And in the colour of our skin, none of us had a choice / You can continue to divide, but the truth will remain / Underneath our skin we all bleed the same’
Subscribe to Hits Radio at https://bit.ly/2JmWevp

Listen to Hits Radio: https://planetradio.co.uk/hits-radio/

Across the UK, on 103FM in Manchester, digital radio, online, via the Hits Radio app and on your smartspeaker.
